              margin-bottom: 15px;
                    "><strong>The Canadian federal election race has tightened, with the Liberals just three points ahead of the Conservatives, according to a recent Ipsos poll</strong>. Mark Carney’s leadership has boosted Liberal support, especially on international issues and standing up to Trump, while Conservative leader Pierre Poilievre is gaining ground on domestic concerns like affordability. Debate performances were mixed, but Carney still leads in overall leadership perception. With support nearly split and regional differences at play, the odds of a majority government are at risk (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-22-04-2025-br1-11-election-details?source=website" target="_blank">election update</a>).</p>
                    
                    <p style="
              font-size: 16px;
              line-height: 1.5;
              border-left: 3px solid #4D3060;
              padding-left: 14px;
              margin-bottom: 15px;
                    "><strong>During a historic address to Italy’s parliament, King Charles made a rare and pointed reference to his role as “King of Canada.”</strong> The symbolic gesture comes amid rising tension between Canada and the US, especially following President Trump’s past remarks about Canada becoming the 51st state. With the King restricted from direct political commentary, his support for Canada has been conveyed through subtle signals, such as wearing Canadian medals and planting a maple tree. While some Canadians want a stronger stance, Charles is navigating a diplomatic tightrope between loyalty to Canada and maintaining ties with Trump (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-22-04-2025-br2-12-charles-diplomatic-tightrope?source=website" target="_blank">Charles’ diplomatic tightrope</a>).</p>
        </mj-text>
